 Environmental Initiatives in the Hotel Sector in Greece: Case Study of the ‘Green Flags’ Project -- tSection 4: Diversified Coastal Tourism and Sustainable Development -- t13. Sustainable Tourism: Utopia or Necessity? The Role of New Forms of Tourism in the Aegean Islands -- t14. Tourism, Culture and Cultural Tourism in Malta: The Revival of Valletta -- t15. Coffee Shop Meets Casino: Cultural Responses to Casino Tourism in Northern Cyprus -- t16. Tourism, Modernisation and Development on the Island of Cyprus: Challenges and Policy Responses -- t17. Rejuvenation, Diversification and Imagery: Sustainability Conflicts for Tourism Policy in the Eastern Adriatic -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Mediterranean coastal regions of Southern Europe have long been world leaders in mass tourism. This book examines some key questions for tourism development in these areas, with implications for similar regions across the world. The standardised forms of mass tourism are diversifying – with more specialised forms, notably those based on nature, culture and heritage, and those catering for special interests. There is a growing spectrum of modes of tourism, with an emphasis on variety, flexibility and permeability. Both mass tourism and the more diversified forms substantially impact on sustainable development. Policies promoting sustainable development are often of two main types: developing smaller-scale, alternative tourism products that are intended to be less damaging to the environment and society, and secondly, attempts to make mass tourism coastal resorts more sustainable. But there has been little critical assessment of these policies, either evaluating their basic assumptions or their successes and failures in practice. This edited book critically examines these issues for varied coastal regions in Southern Europe, including case studies from Spain, Croatia, Turkey, and north and south Cyprus.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEcotourismxEurope, Southern. 0aEcotourismxMediterranean Region. 0aEcotourismzEurope, Southern. 0aEcotourismzMediterranean Region. 0aSustainable developmentxEurope, Southern. 0aSustainable developmentxMediterranean RegionxEurope, SouthernxMediterranean Region. 0aSustainable developmentzEurope, Southern. 0aSustainable developmentzMediterranean Region. 4aSustainability. 4aTourism industry. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Industries / Hospitality, Travel & Tourism.2bisacsh  acoastal tourism.  amass tourism development.  amass tourism.  asustainability.  asustainable development.  asustainable tourism.  atourism development.  atourism diversification.  atourism in coastal regions.  atourism policy.1 aAndriotis, Konstantinos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaidal, Josep A. Ivars, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarke, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBramwell, Bill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBramwell, Bill, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBriassoulis, Helen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampillo-Besses, Xavier, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChatziathanassiou, Artemios, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarcía, Gonzalo Malvárez, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHall, Derek, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMavrogiorgos, Daphne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPollard, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ct